DOCUMENT();

#image scale
$imgScale = .2;

#image aspect ratio
$width = $imgScale*2284;
$height = $imgScale*1636;

loadMacros(   
	"PGstandard.pl",     # Standard macros for PG language
	"MathObjects.pl",
	"PGML.pl",
	"parserPopUp.pl",
	"parserMultiAnswer.pl",
	"parserRadioButtons.pl",
	#"source.pl",        # allows code to be displayed on certain sites.
	#"PGcourse.pl", 	 # Customization file for the course
   	);

TEXT(beginproblem());

##############################################################
#
#  Setup
#
#

Context("Numeric");
#given
$CylinderLength = random(0.5, 1.5, 0.1);# [m]
$FlowVelocity = random(2,6,0.5);# [m/s]

#computation
$WaterDensity = 998;# [kg/m3]
$Ans = 1/3*$WaterDensity*(($FlowVelocity)**2)*$CylinderLength;# [N/m]

#set tolerance
Context()->flags->set(
tolerance=>.01,);

##############################################################
#
#  PGML 
#
#

BEGIN_PGML

[@ image("UBC-FLU-18-055.png", width=>[$width], height=>[$height]) @]*

As shown in the diagram, a thick elliptical cylinder is immersed in a water stream and creates an idealized wake. Pressures upstream and downstream are identical,  [`U_0=[$FlowVelocity]`] [`m/s`] and [`L=[$CylinderLength]`] [`m`]. What is the drag force on the cylinder per unit width into the screen?

[`F=`] [____]{"$Ans"} [`N/m`]

END_PGML

